summary: This is a collection of TexturePacks for my main mod EBD - EveryBodys Different. Body textures from many different authors are offered for diversifying NPCs.
descriptionHtml:
[center][size=5]
TexturePacks
for
EBD - EveryBody's Different
by
MongoMonk
[/size]

Released: 07.03.2014
Last Update: 24.01.2015
Site: [url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/51638/]http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/51638/[/url][/center]

[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Summary[/color][/u][/size][/center]
This page exists to offer several TexturePacks for the skyproc patcher EveryBody's Different (EBD) created by yours truly.

TexturePacks are collections of body textures and a xml file specifying the valid races for each pack. They are put in a certain folder structure which is recognized by EBD. EBD then distributes those textures among NPCs.
You may install as many TexturePacks as you want at the same time. Each installed TexturePack will be considered when patcher distributes the body textures.
Note that even if you're using just one TexturePack then the vanilla textures of all NPCs which are valid for that TexturePack will be replaced by those from the TexturePack.
For more information refer to EBD's site.
Several texture authors kindly gave me permission for publishing their textures. Most TexturePacks are available in UNP and CBBE variants. There is one special pack for MuscularWomen.

The male TexturePacks are even more basic than the female ones. They are completely without face textures. If you need them get them from the original mod or any other male face mod or just do without them (the patcher will then default to your standard face texture files). The BetterMales Pack comes with two mesh variations to show off the mesh feature.

Some TexturePacks contain textures as well as meshes. They are especially marked if they do so.
[b]The meshes contained in the male packs as well as in CBBE Standard and UNP Standard are nude.[/b] Delete the included meshes folder if you do not like that.

Note that these TexturePacks are meant as examples. My support for them will be very limited as I prefer working on my main mod. I hope that the TexturePacks work as a guide, so that everyone may create their own.
Even better would be if the texture authors themselves would offer some TexturePacks of their textures. Let's see if that'll work out.
By the way the TexturePacks are in no way static or fixed. You may mess with them as you like. Remove textures you don't like, add some you like better or replace them. You just have to rerun the patcher if you add/remove any and the changes you made will be automatically recognized by the patcher. The same is true for the meshes of course.


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Requirements[/color][/u][/size][/center]
You need to have EBD and therefore the requirements of EBD are necessary as well.

Download EBD here: [url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/51612/]Clicko[/url]


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Compatibility[/color][/u][/size][/center]
The same compatibility notes as for the main mod apply.

You should only install TexturePacks which match your installed body mod. Exceptions are the TexturePacks which provide body meshes as well. The naked body mesh will automatically be set to those included and therefore they'll work with any setup.


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Details[/color][/u][/size][/center]
Each TexturePack comes with a predefined set of valid races (the selection was done by myself) saved into a xml file by the patcher. You may want to check in the interface that you agree with my selection.
You'll find the TexturePack Editor in the Texture/Mesh Settings panel. You must wait until the patcher has finished importing your load order before opening the TexturePack Editor.
There are some TexturePacks which are a bit special. For one I pre-selected vampire only races for the Khmera TexturePack. It is pretty pale and fits vampires nicely. It's especially nice if you disable vampires for all other TexturePacks, so vampires have their own TexturePack.
Next to mention are the BI Phenotypes TexturePacks. I only enabled them for the human races (Nord, Breton, Imperial, Redguard) as they don't come with face normal maps for other races (in fact the only normal map provided is for Nords). You may of course move the face normal map in its own folder and only enable it for Nords (or all human races) so that the other races point to their standard normal map. That's up to you.

Note that my screenshots in the screenshots section are just random shots while I was doing a quick run through Whiterun. If you want to know how a specific TexturePack looks then go to the original author's site.
You may notice that my screenshots suck. Therefore I'd be quite happy if you could add some of yours.


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Installation[/color][/u][/size][/center]
Use NMM, Mod Organizer or Wrye Bash to install. If you are familiar with Skyrim's folder structure you can of course install manually.
After installing make sure to run EBD and check the "Force Patch" option (if possible).
Since every TexturePack comes with a predefined set of valid races (the selection was done by myself) you may want to check in the interface (the TexturePack Editor) that you agree with my selection.


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Uninstallation[/color][/u][/size][/center]
Again just use any of the tools mentioned above for installation. If you uninstall manually the folders are found in "Textures/EBD", "Meshes/EBD" and "Skyproc Patchers/EBD/TexturePackXmlFiles".
Make sure to run the patcher again if you uninstall a TexturPack. Instead of uninstalling you may quickly enable/disable certain TexturePacks in the TexturePack Editor interface as well.


[center][size=5][u][color=yellow]Texture Tools/VRam Usage[/color][/u][/size][/center]
I tried to keep The VRam and performance impact of the TexturePacks as low as possible. All colour textures have a resolution of 2048px max. (DXT1 compressed) and all normal maps have a resolution of 1024px max. (uncompressed).
If you want to create your own TexturePack I'd recommend doing the same with the textures. I've got 1 GB of VRam and those texture settings work quite well.

The following tools were used to optimize the textures.
[url=http://skyrim.nexusmods.com/mods/13529]SMCO[/url]
Very easy to use. Just click and play. I like it a lot. However, you cannot resize big textures (4096px). For resizing and more options use the tool below.

[url=http://skyrim.nexusmods.com/mods/12801]Optimizer Textures[/url]
Has more options and is a tad more complicated to use. I recommended to use this tool to resize any textures with a resolution greater than 2048px down to 2048px. Especially if you have 1 gb of VRam or less.

A great many thanks to all the texture authors who gave me permission. You're doing a great job!
Also a big thank you to bla08 for providing consistent feedback and even updating some texture packs.

Every TexturePack comes with its own "Credits.txt" where I list all the necessary credits from each original mod. If I missed any author or messed up some permission I am very sorry. Please contact me so I may correct my error.
Most TexturePacks use a combination of their own body normal maps and that created by Wast1980.
Most CBBE TexturePacks use No More Ugly Bronze Shine by COTS.

files.name: UNP - Textures - True Daughters
files.changelogHtml:
UNP TexturePack fixes thanks to bla08:

- AnTiWoMaAgNoT: added face textures + racial variations
- BI Phenotypes: added face textures with fixed neck + racial variations
- True Daughters: fixed Breton neck seam

Furthermore bla08 has optimized those TexturePacks to have a better look while still maintaining a small file size. Many thanks to him.
Note that I have NOT tested the TexturePacks but provide them as they were given to me.
